Migrating from Java 11 to Java 17 brings significant shifts in how the JVM manages memory.
The most notable change is the retirement of older, non-deterministic collectors in favor of modern, low-latency options

1. The Big Removal: CMS is GoneThe Concurrent Mark Sweep (CMS) collector, which was already deprecated in Java 11, has been completely removed in Java 17.
  The Impact: If your Java 11 application used -XX:+UseConcMarkSweepGC, it will fail to start in Java 17. You must switch to G1, ZGC, or Shenandoah

2. G1GC: Still the Default, but Faster
    The Garbage-First (G1) collector remains the default for both versions, but the Java 17 version is significantly more optimized.
    Full GC Parallelism: Java 11's G1 had some single-threaded phases during Full GC.
          By Java 17, G1 is much better at cleaning up memory concurrently, leading to shorter "Stop-the-World" pauses.
    NUMA Awareness: Java 17 includes enhancements for Non-Uniform Memory Access (NUMA), allowing G1 to allocate memory more efficiently on modern multi-socket servers.
3.
Feature        Java 11                                            Java 17
ZGC            Experimental (-XX:+UnlockExperimentalVMOptions)    Production Ready
Shenandoah      Only in some builds (like RedHat)                 Production Ready in most OpenJDK builds
Pause Times    ~10ms (ZGC)                                        Sub-millisecond (ZGC in Java 17)
Max Heap Size   4 TB                                              16 TB

4.Memory Footprint and Efficiency
Java 17 is generally more "polite" with memory:
Prompt Memory Return: Modern collectors in Java 17 are much better at returning unused heap memory back to the Operating System.
Deduplication: String deduplication (reducing the memory taken by identical strings) was enhanced and made available for more collectors in Java 17.



