public methods in interfaces, but protected methods are strictly forbidden?
    The rules for access modifiers in Java interfaces have evolved significantly between Java 8 and Java 21, 
    but the restriction on protected remains a fundamental language rule.

1. Public Methods (The Standard)
    By default, all abstract methods in an interface are implicitly public.
    Even if you don't type the keyword, the compiler adds it for you.
    Abstract Methods: void doWork(); is treated as public abstract void doWork();.
    Default/Static Methods: These are also public by default, allowing them to be accessed by any class that implements the interface.

2. The "No Protected" Rule
    Interfaces are meant to define a public API—a contract between the service and the outside world.
    Why? protected is designed to allow access to subclasses or classes in the same package. 
          Since interfaces are meant to be implemented (often by classes in entirely different packages),
              protected contradicts the "public contract" philosophy of an interface.
    Result: Attempting to use protected will result in a compilation error: "Modifier 'protected' not allowed here."

3. Private Methods (Java 9+)
    While you can't use protected, Java 9 introduced private methods. 
    These are used for "helper" logic that you don't want to expose to the implementing classes.
      Private Instance Methods: Used to share code between multiple default methods.
      Private Static Methods: Used to share code between multiple static methods.

On abstract method can we use static keyword ?
  The short answer is no; you cannot combine the static and abstract modifiers on a method in a Java interface.
  In Java, these two keywords represent fundamentally opposing concepts, making them logically incompatible.

Why they cannot coexist
  To understand why static abstract is not allowed, we have to look at what each modifier actually does:
  abstract: This is a placeholder. It says, "This method exists, but it has no implementation here. 
    An implementing class must provide the body." It relies on dynamic dispatch (polymorphism) at runtime.
  static: This belongs to the interface/class itself, not to an instance.
      A static method must have a body (implementation) because it is called directly via the interface name (e.g., MyInterface.myMethod()).
  
    If a method were both, you would have a method that must be called without an instance (static) but has no code to execute (abstract),
      which would result in a crash or undefined behavior.

The Modern Way: Static Methods in Interfaces
  Since Java 8, you can have static methods in interfaces, but they must be concrete (they must have a body).
  Usage & Benefits:
      Static methods in interfaces are used for utility or helper methods that are relevant to the interface's domain
      but don't need to be overridden by implementing classes.
      Encapsulation of Logic: It keeps helper methods tied to the interface they belong to rather than creating a separate InterfaceUtils class.
      Security: Since they are static, they cannot be overridden by an implementing class. This ensures the logic remains exactly as defined.
      Namespace Organization: It provides a clear way to call methods related to the interface.
      public interface Vehicle {
          // Standard abstract method
          void startEngine();
      
          // Static utility method
          static boolean isElectric(String fuelType) {
              return "Electric".equalsIgnoreCase(fuelType);
            }
      }

// Calling the static method
boolean check = Vehicle.isElectric("Petrol");
