The "Design Rule":
    Most experienced developers follow the rule: "Favor Composition over Inheritance."
    Inheritance is very rigid.
    If you use Is-A for everything, you end up with deep, complex class trees that are impossible to change.
    Use Has-A whenever possible, and only use Is-A when there is a clear, permanent hierarchical relationship.


Marker Interface:
  A marker interface is an empty interface — it has no methods. Its main purpose is to mark a class so that the JVM or frameworks can handle it in a special way.
a) Serializable
    Package: java.io.Serializable
    Marks a class as serializable, i.e., its objects can be converted to a byte stream (for saving to file or sending over network).
    No methods in Serializable — JVM handles serialization based on the marker.
    
    import java.io.*;
    class Person implements Serializable {
        private String name;
        private int age;  
        Person(String name, int age) {
            this.name = name;
            this.age = age;
        }
           public String toString() {
            return name + " : " + age;
        }
    }
    public class TestSerialization {
        public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
            Person p = new Person("Alice", 25);
            // Serialization
            FileOutputStream fos = new FileOutputStream("person.ser");
            ObjectOutputStream oos = new ObjectOutputStream(fos);
            oos.writeObject(p); // JVM checks if Person implements Serializable
            oos.close();  
            // Deserialization
            FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream("person.ser");
            ObjectInputStream ois = new ObjectInputStream(fis);
            Person p2 = (Person) ois.readObject();
            ois.close();
            System.out.println(p2); // Alice : 25
        }
    }
    Usage:  Without implementing Serializable, ObjectOutputStream will throw NotSerializableException.

  b) Cloneable
      Package: java.lang.Cloneable
      Marks a class as allowing its objects to be cloned using Object.clone().
      No methods — the JVM checks the interface.
      class Person implements Cloneable {
          String name;
          Person(String name) {
              this.name = name;
          }
          protected Object clone() throws CloneNotSupportedException {
              return super.clone();
          }
      }
      public class TestClone {
          public static void main(String[] args) throws CloneNotSupportedException {
              Person p1 = new Person("Bob");
              Person p2 = (Person) p1.clone(); // JVM allows because implements Cloneable
              System.out.println(p2.name); // Bob
          }
      }
      Usage: If a class doesn’t implement Cloneable, calling clone() throws CloneNotSupportedException.

  c) Remote
      Package: java.rmi.Remote
      Marks a class as remote object for Java RMI (Remote Method Invocation).
      Used by the RMI system to allow method calls across JVMs.
  d) Custom Marker Interface
      You can create your own marker interface to flag classes for some framework logic.
      interface Auditable { } // Marker interface    
      class Employee implements Auditable {
          String name;
          Employee(String name) { this.name = name; }
      }      
      class AuditService {
          void audit(Object obj) {
              if (obj instanceof Auditable) {
                  System.out.println("Auditing object: " + obj);
              } else {
                  System.out.println("Not auditable");
              }
          }
      }     
      public class TestMarker {
          public static void main(String[] args) {
              Employee e = new Employee("Alice");
              new AuditService().audit(e); // Auditing object
          }
      }

