How to prevent clonable and serilizable in singleton class
  1. Preventing Cloning
  Even if your Singleton doesn't implement Cloneable, a subclass might, or someone could use reflection. 
  To strictly prevent this, override the clone() method from the Object class and explicitly throw an exception.
    @Override
    protected Object clone() throws CloneNotSupportedException {
        // Prevent cloning by throwing an exception
        throw new CloneNotSupportedException("Cloning of this class is prohibited");
    }
  2. Preventing Serialization Issues
  When a Singleton is serialized and then deserialized, the JVM creates a new instance of the object by default. 
  To prevent this, you must implement the readResolve() method.
  The JVM calls readResolve() after the object is deserialized; by returning your existing instance, you ensure the newly created "garbage" instance is discarded.
  
    protected Object readResolve() {
        // Return the existing instance instead of the new one
        return INSTANCE;
    }

The "Pro-Tip": Use an Enum
  If you want to avoid all this boilerplate, the most "witty" and effective solution is to use an Enum.
  In Java, Enums are specialized classes that the JVM guarantees will be singletons.
  They handle serialization automatically and strictly prohibit cloning and reflection-based instantiation.
  
  public enum EnumSingleton {
      INSTANCE;
  
      public void doSomething() {
          // Your logic here
      }
  }
  Note: Using an Enum is widely considered the best way to implement a Singleton in Java because it provides all the protections mentioned above for free, 
  with zero extra code.

